pull the wool over someone's eyes.data-term: pull the wool over someone's eyes

examples.en: The spy betrayed his country.
His voice betrayed his nervousness.
He felt that she had betrayed him.
Rachel felt hurt and betrayed.
She had betrayed her parents' trust.
Her smile betrayed her true feelings.
You betrayed me. You broke your word.
He was betrayed by a scheming friend.
We were betrayed by a perfidious ally.
It dawned on him that she had betrayed him.
A thin pillar of smoke betrayed their campsite.
His face betrayed nothing (=showed no emotion).
He swore vengeance on the man who betrayed him.
She betrayed her own people by supporting the enemy.
He promised to wreak vengeance on those who had betrayed him.
They betrayed their country by selling its secrets to other governments.
The crumpled sheets betrayed the fact that someone had been sleeping there.
You betrayed your father's trust (=did something bad even though he trusted you).
He was a traitor who betrayed his country by selling military secrets to the enemy.
No prince of the house of Lancaster betrayed a wish to renew the quarrel with the Church. (J. A. Froude, History of England, Vol. I, 1858)
